SIMPLE: inflection
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inflection
<hw>In*flec"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>inflexio</ets> : cf. F. <ets>inflexion</ets>. See
<er>Inflect</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>inflecxion</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of inflecting,
or the state of being inflected.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A bend; a fold; a curve; a turn; a twist.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A slide, modulation, or accent of the voice; <as>as,
the rising and the falling <ex>inflection</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Gram.)</fld> <def>The variation or change which
words undergo to mark case, gender, number, comparison, tense, person,
mood, voice, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Any change or
modification in the pitch or tone of the voice.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A departure from the monotone, or reciting note, in
chanting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Opt.)</fld> <def>Same as
<er>Diffraction</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Point of inflection</b></col> <fld>(Geom.)</fld>, <cd>the
point on opposite sides of which a curve bends in contrary
ways.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inflectional</ent>⟦br⟧
